The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Heavy Engineering Corporation (HEC) has scaled up its net sales target for the next fiscal to Rs 450 crore, buoyed by the companys results in 2006. The companys net sales in the year was Rs 324 crore against a target of Rs 300 crore. The companys net profit till December was Rs 7.21 crore. The company is also mulling outsourcing options. The company hopes to win private orders after Posco and Czech company Skoda lay out their projects.

 Simplex Infrastructures Ltd has bagged projects worth Rs 825 crore in India and abroad, including construction of industrial structures, malls and long-distance water intake and delivery systems. Over 50 per cent of the order comprises projects abroad that include construction of the Ahmara Grand Plaza, a luxury residential tower at Qatar.

 Nitin Fire Protection Industries Ltd has filed its draft red herring prospectus with the Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) for its initial public offering of 38.5 lakh equity shares of Rs 10 each for cash at a premium, to be decided through book-building. The issue will constitute 29.37 per cent of the post-issue paid-up capital of the company.

 Chennai-based ReadyTestGo (RTG) has entered into a software-testing partnership with Sun Microsystems. As part of the agreement, Sun Microsystems will market RTGs performance engineering solutions to its corporate customers, while RTG will deliver the testing services from its facilities in Chennai.

 Time Technoplast Ltd has filed a draft red herring prospectus with the Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) to issue 52,21,500 equities of Rs 10 each for cash at a premium to be decided through book-building. The company will reserve 261,100 shares for employees.

 Surana Industries Ltd has been listed on the National Stock Exchange. The shares have been admitted for dealing at a face value of Rs 10 each. The trading will be in the normal market segment compulsory demats for all investors.

 i-mate has launched i-mate SPL, a mid-range hybrid smartphone. The product is a GSM/GPRS-enabled tri-band phone with 65k, 2.2 colour LCD screen, MiniSD memory and expansion, integrated antenna and Bluetooth compatibility. The product comes for Rs 17,500.

 HOV Services will take control of TRAC Holdings and SAM Holdings and invest $3.74 million to acquire its 30 per cent interest in TRAC and SAM. The two companies are expected to deliver more than $17 million of profitable revenues for 2007-08.

